    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "70b366e0_7279c00e",
        "filename": "util/win/loader_lock.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 43,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-12-03T05:09:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My point here is that a thread ID is not semantically a handle in any sense, right? There is a way to refer to threads by HANDLEs, but it’s not this. If you’ve got a choice between two incompatible types used to contain these values, and one of them is semantically inappropriate, I don’t think that’s the one you should choose to frame your work in terms of.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 43,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 43,
        "endChar": 74
      },
      "revId": "11f748b78f9200d3e5cdd96b90c5d7704851a6bd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4db77ecf_3dd342cd",
        "filename": "util/win/loader_lock.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 43,
      "author": {
        "id": 1149139
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-12-03T15:31:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Internally Windows uses the handle allocator to generated PIDs/TIDs and stores everything as HANDLEs (for example CLIENT_ID uses two handles for PID and TID which is reflected here) so really HANDLE is the correct type and DWORD is not. If I wanted to be a pedant about it I probably should extract the UniqueThread handle from the TEB\u0027s CLIENT_ID and do the comparison with that as that ensures some unexpected bits are not set which are being truncated by GetCurrentThreadId.\n\nOf course if the TID happened to be larger than 2^32 which is pretty unlikely things would start breaking anyway so it\u0027s probably a moot point. As it\u0027s not likely in practice I\u0027ll just cast the other way.",
      "parentUuid": "70b366e0_7279c00e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 43,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 43,
        "endChar": 74
      },
      "revId": "11f748b78f9200d3e5cdd96b90c5d7704851a6bd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9305df90_76a935c2",
        "filename": "util/win/loader_lock.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 43,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-12-03T16:56:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Internally Windows uses the handle allocator to generated PIDs/TIDs and stores everything as HANDLEs (for example CLIENT_ID uses two handles for PID and TID which is reflected here) so really HANDLE is the correct type and DWORD is not.\n\nThat aspect of the interface is regarded as a bug, or at the very least, a historical artifact. Since it’s not actually publicly documented for use, we can’t draw much more of a conclusion than “Windows-internal structs rarely change even when repurposed, and its source is full of casts anyway.”\n\nIs the allocator even really what’s important? Once allocated, process and thread IDs are valid system-wide in a strictly numerical context, and are entirely meaningless as handles, right? This is in contrast to proper process and thread handles, which may have different values in different processes despite referring to the same object.\n\nThe other thing you could do, that might be acceptable to both of us (although we might also agree it’s overkill) would be to compare peb-\u003eLoaderLock-\u003eOwningThread to teb-\u003eClientId-\u003eUniqueThread. It’s more undocumented internals, but we’re using undocumented internals anyway. It keeps everything the same type (no casts, which is something we shoot for, even if Microsoft doesn’t), uses information obtained directly from the system, and it’s also exactly where RtlEnterCriticalSection() pulls the OwningThread from (because an NT-level interface wouldn’t actually call the Win32-level GetCurrentThreadId(), although this is exactly what GetCurrentThreadId() does too).",
      "parentUuid": "4db77ecf_3dd342cd",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 43,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 43,
        "endChar": 74
      },
      "revId": "11f748b78f9200d3e5cdd96b90c5d7704851a6bd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "309ea021_8f889ea2",
        "filename": "util/win/loader_lock.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 43,
      "author": {
        "id": 1149139
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-12-03T19:08:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Of course it\u0027d be far simpler to just use the undocumented RtlIsCriticalSectionLockedByThread NTDLL export which does exactly that, compares the CS TID against the TEB\u0027s ClientId-\u003eUniqueThread, but I don\u0027t want to require linking to NTDLL.LIB (where available), I don\u0027t know how far back that function goes (according to https://www.geoffchappell.com/studies/windows/win32/ntdll/api/index.htm it was introduced in 5.2 so it\u0027s might be okay) and I don\u0027t want to dynamically link to it because I want to avoid taking the loader lock when you could be inside the loader lock (even if it\u0027s supposed to be fine being locked recursively). As we have all the internal types in crashpad, I\u0027ll just update it to use the TEB method and not call GetCurrentThreadId at all.",
      "parentUuid": "9305df90_76a935c2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 43,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 43,
        "endChar": 74
      },
      "revId": "11f748b78f9200d3e5cdd96b90c5d7704851a6bd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
